<DOC><DOCNO> AP891101-0151 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1906EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Crackdown     11-01 0179</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Korea-Crackdown,0184</SECOND><HEAD>Security Authorities Arrest 120 Radical Students, Dissidents</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prosecutors said Wednesday that 120radical students and dissidents have been charged with anti-U.S.,anti-government protests and ideological links to North Korea.   The Public Prosecutors' Office said charges have been broughtagainst 82 radical students and 38 dissidents who allegedly armedthemselves with North Korea's revolutionary ideas to overthrowSouth Korea.   Prosecutors said the 120 radicals have been caught in afive-month crackdown. They said about 40,000 pro-North Korean bookshave been seized this year.   The prosecutors pledged a ``systematic and steady'' crackdown,saying pro-North Korean forces have instigated violent protestscalling for the withdrawal of U.S. troops based in South Koreaunder a mutual defense pact.   Government officials claimed radicals have used campuses todisseminate pro-North Korean ideas and attacked U.S. military anddiplomatic facilities to dramatize their campaign.   Radical students, a powerful minority on campuses, have failedto earn broad support because of their violent tactics andideological extremism since President Roh Tae-woo took office inFebruary 1988 and carried out reforms.</TEXT></DOC>